ce:section.ce:para:
As is common in many types of CNDs, particularly those where the fluorescence properties did not specifically rely in molecular species (embedded in the matrix and/or linked to the surface), the emission of our current CNMs/CNDs is dependent on the excitation wavelength (λ
                        exc). Excitation between 250 and 340 nm led to similar profiles and emission maxima, although with increasing intensities along that range, with the highest intensity nearly 410 nm. Illumination of the samples under lower energies produce easily observable red shifts in the emission maximum, particularly above 380 nm, which are accompanied by an intense hypochromism. When excited at 420 nm, the emission maximum is around 485 nm, with the emission cut-off near 700 nm (Fig. 4
                        ).
